<span id="fn_1360"></span>[221:13](kj073.htm#fr_1364.md) *Wani-zaka*. For
the setting of jars *conf*. Sect LX, Note 20.

<span id="fn_1361"></span>[221:14](kj073.htm#fr_1365.md) *Wakara gaha*. It
is what is now called the Idzumi-gaha. Of Wakara we have nothing but an
altogether untenable etymology given in the parallel passage of the
"Chronicles."

<span id="fn_1362"></span>[221:15](kj073.htm#fr_1366.md) More literally,
"each having put the river in the middle, and mutually challenging."

<span id="fn_1363"></span>[221:16](kj073.htm#fr_1367.md) *I.e.*,
"challenging." The more likely etymology of *Idzumi*, which is written
with the character <span id="img_22301"></span> ![](img/22301.jpg), is
"source "or "spring."

<span id="fn_1364"></span>[221:17](kj073.htm#fr_1368.md) The original has
the very curious expressions <span id="img_22302"></span>
![](img/22302.jpg), literally," people of the side-building," which was
a great crux to the early editors, Motowori is probably right in
interpreting it in the sense of "the other side," *i.e.*, "the enemy."

<span id="fn_1365"></span>[221:18](kj073.htm#fr_1369.md) <span
id="img_22303"></span> ![](img/22303.jpg); literally "the arrow to be
